Part 5

The staff room of the Bagbazar shelter had seven chairs and one long wooden bench where the junior volunteers sat.

Vikram stood near the window.

The neem trees outside were losing their leaves, the yellow blades falling silent onto the courtyard stone.

"I am going," Vikram said.

Sarita looked up from the table.

She was holding a glass of red tea, her hands trembling slightly against the warm glass.

"Where?" she asked.

"Nowhere," Vikram said. "Just out."

"But the shelter, Vikram," one of the senior patients, an old tailor named Ghosh, said. "The Barasat license is still pending. The distributors won't talk to us if you're not here."

"They will talk to Sarita," Vikram said. "She has the register."

"We need you, Baba," Ananya said, from the corner of the bench.

She was eighteen now.

She was still holding the ledger with the green cloth cover, her fingers tracing the seam of the spine.

"The kids at the school ask when you are coming to tell the crow story. They have been waiting since Tuesday."

"Tell them the crow flew away," Vikram said.

He looked at her, his face quiet.

"I want to be a free bird, Ananya."

"Even a bird has a nest," Sarita said.

"Only when it is tired," Vikram said.

He picked up his small leather bag.

He had left the second shirt on the bench. He had only the clothes he wore — a faded cotton kurta and the rubber slippers he'd bought at the Shobhabazar market.

He walked out.

He didn't use the main wooden door.

He walked through the side corridor, passed the kitchen where the red tea was still simmering on the coal stove, and went out into the lane.

---

For three years, he lived on the streets of Bagbazar.

He slept on the verandah of the Ramkrishna Mission, his head resting on his rolled-up bag.

The monks knew him as the old man who swept the steps before the morning prayers.

They offered him dal and rice in the noon.

He ate what they gave, washed his plate at the tap, and sat near the river bank for the rest of the day.

The children near the school started calling him Budha Baba.

Not because he was old.

Because he had the time to sit on the concrete drain edge and listen to their stories about the street dogs and the broken kites.

He didn't have a phone.

If the shelter needed him, Ramu's nephew would walk down to the river bank and tell him.

But they rarely called.

They had learned to run the math themselves.

---

The call came on a Tuesday morning in July 2018.

Vikram was sleeping on the verandah of the Mission, the rain from the Hooghly river spraying light drops over his feet.

Ramu's nephew came running, his shirt wet, holding a plastic pouch containing Vikram's old Nokia phone.

"Baba," the boy said, out of breath. "Ananya called. From the shelter."

Vikram took the phone.

The screen was scratched, the battery showing only one bar of green light.

"Ananya?"

"Baba," her voice was fast, tight with the specific panic of the emergency ward. "It's Kavita. The girl from the Barasat branch. She got her report yesterday. She is at the bypass bridge. She wants to jump."

"I am coming," Vikram said.

He didn't take the bag.

He left it on the Mission verandah, near the sweeper's broom.

He ran.

His rubber slippers were thin, the soles sliding on the wet mud of the Bagbazar lanes.

The bypass bridge was two kilometers away.

When he reached, Kavita was standing on the concrete ledge of the railing, her hands holding the iron pipe, looking down at the railway tracks below.

The rain was heavier now, the water running fast along the concrete.

A crowd of truck drivers had gathered at a distance, shouting, but nobody had gone close.

Vikram walked onto the bridge.

He didn't shout.

He didn't tell her that life was beautiful.

He simply stood beside her on the ledge, his faded kurta soaked through, his feet cold in the slippers.

"The water is dirty," Vikram said, looking at the tracks.

Kavita turned her head slowly.

Her face was white, her eyes wet with the rain.

"I have the bad blood, Baba," she whispered.

"I know," Vikram said. "Ananya had it too. She is still writing the ledger."

He held out his hand.

His hand was rough, the calluses yellow and hard, the nails grey with river sand.

"Come," he said. "Ramu's nephew has the tea ready. It is cheap tea, but it is hot."

She looked at his hand.

She looked at the tracks below.

Then she stepped down.

She didn't cry. She simply took his hand, her fingers cold and trembling against his calluses.

Vikram led her to the ambulance the police had brought.

A local MLA, who had arrived in a white Ambassador car with a red light on the top, stepped out.

He recognized Vikram from the old Kolkata press meets.

"Ahuja saab," the MLA said, holding an umbrella over Vikram's head. "Get in. The car will drop you to the hospital."

Vikram pushed the umbrella aside.

"The car is too clean," Vikram said. "It will get wet."

He walked away.

He crossed the bypass road, his slippers sliding on the mud.

The rain had stopped for a moment, the sun coming through the grey clouds, turning the wet road into a line of shining silver.

Behind him, a crowd had gathered near the bridge.

A strike was happening, the local workers shouting slogans, throwing stones at the passing auto rickshaws.

A motorcycle came fast from the wrong side of the divider, its headlight off, its engine roaring over the shouts of the crowd.

Vikram didn't hear the horn.

He was looking at the well tap of the shelter visible between the buildings, thinking of the red tea that would be waiting.

A sharp, dry sound of brakes.

Then the impact.

He felt the road rising to meet his shoulder.

He felt his rubber slipper flying off his foot.

And then the darkness came, quiet and cold, like the shadow of the neem trees in the Bagbazar courtyard.

---

*"Please... side... please... give a little side..."*

The voice wasn't loud.

Yet it cut through the noise of the casualty corridor.

An old man lying on a stretcher, his white cotton shirt brown near the shoulder, one rubber slipper still remaining on his right foot.

The NGO girl walking beside him, her left elbow bleeding, her sleeve torn.

She bent down.

Removed the remaining slipper.

Placed both carefully under the stretcher.

"It doesn't look nice," she said. "Wearing only one slipper."

